sponsive-and-adaptive-web-design.md";s:3:"url";s:48:"/blog/what-is-responsive-and-adaptive-web-design";s:4:"data";a:41:{s:5:"title";s:34:"Responsive vs. Adaptive Web Design";s:9:"photo_url";a:1:{s:101:"http://d13yacurqjgara.cloudfront.net/users/66105/screenshots/1457275/site_updates.png" style="display";s:217:"<span id="hs_cos_wrapper_post_body" class="hs_cos_wrapper hs_cos_wrapper_meta_field hs_cos_wrapper_type_rich_text" style="" data-hs-cos-general-type="meta_field" data-hs-cos-type="rich_text"><div class="content blog">";}i:0;s:158:"<h3>When making the transition to building responsive or adaptive websites, the hardest part can be getting started. Here are some things to think about.</h3>";i:1;s:336:"<p>There are two common keywords that are becoming more and more talked about in the world of web design, responsive and adaptive. If you are planning on a new website, knowing these terms and their differences is important. It will give you an idea of what is possible and what a designer like me can give you for your new website.</p>";i:2;s:11:"<!--more-->";i:3;s:37:"<h3>Understanding the Difference</h3>";i:4;s:382:"<p>A responsive web site design uses CSS media queries to resize and rearrange the pages elements based on the size of your browser. Those accessing the page from a laptop or a PC will get the full-sized version. Those on tablets and mobile devices (iPhone or Android) see a different arrangement. This type of web design is easier to implement and support than adaptive design.</p>";s:396:"<p>Before responsive web design, most websites dealt with tablets and smart phones by offering a sandboxed version of the site designed for the smaller browser size. This limited options available to those users since most of these special designs tried to reduce bandwidth use and didn't cater to the large number of device resolutions we now have to deal with. Here is a good quote to summarize";s:4:"</p>";i:5;s:6:"</div>";s:189:"<blockquote>There’s still a lot of resistance, though. That’s why the idea of creating separate silos for “mobile” devices is initially so appealing. But that approach won’t scale";s:494:"it’s just not practical to spend equal time and effort crafting different endpoints for iPhone, Android, Palm, Kindle, iPad, etc. The solution is to either reject part of your potential audience and concentrate only on a subset of users like, say, just iPhone users …or you can embrace responsive design. The first option is the cure that kills the patient. The second option might seem intimidating at first, but it’s going to become increasingly accepted. Inevitable, even.</blockquote>";i:6;s:26:"<div class="content blog">";i:7;s:439:"<p>Adaptive web design, on the other hand, is an enhancement of responsive design as I see it. With this type of design, the website detects the accessing device's identity. With that information, the website activates or deactivates functionality. It also rearranges elements the same as responsive design. By creating a unique combination of features based on device type, the user gets all the functionality their device can handle.</p>";s:37:"<h3>Three differences between the two";s:5:"</h3>";i:8;s:4:"<ol>";i:9;s:140:"<li>Responsive design changes based on the browser window size while adaptive design changes due to rules based on device capabilities.</li>";i:10;s:177:"<li>Responsive design offers the same elements to every user independent of device while adaptive design offers different elements to users based on their accessing device.</li>";i:11;s:140:"<li>Responsive design runs from media queries while adaptive design often uses advanced scripts to detect device and present functions.</li>";i:12;s:5:"</ol>";i:13;s:453:"<p>Responsive design works only with the layout of the browser window. It uses media queries through CSS to get information and to change the website in response. Adaptive design uses scripts to detect the device and to make certain elements available to the browser based on that information. People accessing an adaptive design website from two different devices may see something very different because their device is so different in capability.</p>";s:14:"<img src="http";s:45:"//static.simp.sn/assets/responsivedesign2.jpg";s:7:"content";s:4:"true";s:11:"content_raw";s:4:"true";s:5:"_file";s:126:"/Users/David/Dropbox/GitHub/simpsn.com/www.simpsn.com/_content/3-blog/2012-12-09-what-is-responsive-and-adaptive-web-design.md";s:11:"_local_path";s:64:"/3-blog/2012-12-09-what-is-responsive-and-adaptive-web-design.md";s:10:"_order_key";i:1355029200;s:13:"datetimestamp";N;s:9:"datestamp";i:1355029200;s:4:"date";s:12:"Dec 09, 2012";s:4:"time";N;s:7:"numeric";N;s:13:"last_modified";i:1406656126;s:10:"_is_hidden";b:0;s:9:"_is_draft";b:0;s:4:"slug";s:42:"what-is-responsive-and-adaptive-web-design";s:7:"_folder";s:4:"blog";s:9:"_basename";s:56:"2012-12-09-what-is-responsive-and-adaptive-web-design.md";s:9:"_filename";s:53:"2012-12-09-what-is-responsive-and-adaptive-web-design";s:9:"_is_entry";i:1;s:8:"_is_page";i:0;s:3:"url";s:48:"/blog/what-is-responsive-and-adaptive-web-design";s:9:"permalink";s:65:"http://simpsn.com/blog/what-is-responsive-and-adaptive-web-design";}}s:96:"2013-01-13-replacing-deprecated-functions-in-phpthumb-to-be-compatible-with-php-version-5-3-0.md";a:5:{s:6:"folder";s:4:"blog";s:4:"path";s:104:"/3-blog/2013-01-13-replacing-deprecated-functions-in-phpthumb-to-be-compatible-with-php-version-5-3-0.md";s:4:"file";s:96:"2013-01-13-replacing-deprecated-functions-in-phpthumb-to-be-compatible-with-php-version-5-3-0.md";s:3:"url";s:88:"/blog/replacing-deprecated-functions-in-phpthumb-to-be-compatible-with-php-version-5-3-0";s:4:"data";a:23:{s:5:"title";s:34:"Replacing deprecated PHP functions";s:9:"photo_url";s:91:"http://www.techwench.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/All-about-Web-Development-Companies.jpg";s:7:"content";s:4:"true";s:11:"content_raw";s:4:"true";s:5:"_file";s:166:"/Users/David/Dropbox/GitHub/simpsn.com/www.simpsn.com/_